// Day 1  Google home page to login page
package testing;
import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
public class Sample {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
		System.setProperty("Webdriver.chrome.driver","D:\\My files\\Yellow matics\\testing file");
		WebDriver d = new ChromeDriver();
		d.get("https://www.google.com/");
		System.out.println(d.getTitle());
		System.out.println(d.getCurrentUrl());
		d.manage().window().maximize();
		d.findElement(By.className("gb_Z")).click();
		Thread.sleep(2000);
		d.findElement(By.cssSelector(".button.button--medium.header__aside__button.button--desktop.button--tablet.button--mobile")).click();
		Thread.sleep(2000);
		d.close();
		d.quit();
	}
}

// Report of issues faced 

Selenium Automation – Issue Report
Project: Selenium WebDriver with Chrome
Browser: Chrome 143
Operating System: Windows 11
Language: Java


1. CDP Version Mismatch Error
Error:
Unable to find CDP implementation matching 143

Reason:
Chrome was updated to version 143, but the Selenium version in use did not contain the matching Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP) library.
The project was also using selenium-server.jar, which is meant only for Selenium Grid and remote execution, not for local test execution.
Solution:
	1. Removed selenium-server.jar from the project.
	2. Downloaded selenium-java-4.39.0.zip from the Selenium website.
	3. Added selenium-java-4.39.0.jar and all jar files from the libs folder to the project.
	4. Updated ChromeDriver to version 143.
This added selenium-devtools-v143.jar to the project, which resolved the warning.


2. driver.close() Not Working
Issue:
The driver.close() method was not closing the browser, but driver.quit() was working.
Reason:
Because selenium-server.jar was being used, Chrome was started as a remote session instead of a local browser session. This caused Selenium to lose the active window reference.
Solution:
After removing selenium-server.jar and using selenium-java with its libraries, Chrome started as a normal local browser. This fixed the window handling and driver.close() began working correctly.


3. InvalidSelectorException (Multiple Class Names)
Error:
InvalidSelectorException: Compound class names not permitted

Reason:
By.className() can accept only one class name. The HTML element had multiple classes separated by spaces, which caused Selenium to treat it as an invalid selector.
Example of wrong usage:
By.className("button button--medium header__aside__button")

Solution:
Used CSS selectors or a single unique class instead.
Correct examples:
By.cssSelector(".header__aside__button")

or
By.cssSelector(".button.button--medium.header__aside__button")



4. Google Login Blocked
Error shown by Google:
This browser or app may not be secure

Reason:
Google blocks all automated login attempts. When Selenium controls Chrome, Google detects automation and blocks the login to protect the account.
Solution:
Instead of automating the login page, Selenium was configured to use a real Chrome profile that is already logged in.
Steps:
	1. Logged in to Gmail using normal Chrome.
	2. Found Chrome profile path from chrome://version.
	3. Passed that profile to Selenium using ChromeOptions.
This allowed Gmail to open already logged in without being blocked.


5. ChromeDriver Version Mismatch
Issue:
Chrome updated to version 143, but ChromeDriver was an older version.
Reason:
ChromeDriver must match the major Chrome version to work correctly.
Solution:
Downloaded and installed ChromeDriver version 143.0.7499.192, which is compatible with Chrome 143.


Final Best Practices
	1. Never use selenium-server.jar for running local Selenium tests. Always use selenium-java.jar and all jars from the libs folder.
	2. Chrome, ChromeDriver, and Selenium versions must match to avoid CDP errors.
	3. By.className() must never contain spaces. Use By.cssSelector() or By.xpath() for elements with multiple classes.
	4. Do not automate Google login pages. Use an already logged-in Chrome profile.
	5. Update ChromeDriver whenever Chrome updates.


This setup is now stable, compatible with Chrome 143, and working correctly.
